    <feedback>
      Florence's flowers should betray her emotions during the deception revelation (Ch 10), but no flower colors are mentioned in either confrontation passage. Her character card emphasizes 'The flowers betray emotions she tries to keep controlled—petals tightening when irritated, color shifts when pleased or embarrassed' and 'emotional flower displays make it hard to hide feelings even when she wants to.' The revelation scene in Ch10 passage 1 (False Wisdom) is highly emotional—Florence makes 'a small sound' of distress when caught, her platform 'goes very still,' she's defensive and hurt. But there are no flower color descriptions. Ch10 passage 2 (The Deception) is even more emotional—Florence shouts (which the text notes 'Florence doesn't shout'), she's bitter, in pain, feeling small and manipulated. But again, no flower colors mentioned. This is a missed opportunity for visual storytelling and contradicts the character card's emphasis that her flowers betray emotions she wants to hide. During these confrontations, her flowers should be displaying her emotional state—perhaps mortified colors, defensive tightening, shifts between anger and hurt—precisely because she CAN'T hide her feelings even though she wants to.
    </feedback>
